<article itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/NewsArticle" class="article-single standalone intro-standard " id="">
      <div class="column-wrapper">
    <div class="left-column">
        <header class="article-header">
            <h4 class="post-upperdek">
      Yes, that Gabe Newell    &mdash;
</h4>
            <h1 itemprop="headline">Aston Martin’s Valkyrie is going racing, but only after a power cut</h1>
            <h2 itemprop="description">The engine and aerodynamics both need to be pegged back to satisfy the rule book.</h2>
            <section class="post-meta">

  
<p class="byline" itemprop="author creator" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
      <a itemprop="url" href="https://arstechnica.com/author/ars-contributors/"  rel="author" ><span itemprop="name">Alex Goy</span></a>
    -    <time class="date" data-time="1696437444" datetime="2023-10-04T16:37:24+00:00">Oct 4, 2023 4:37 pm UTC</time>
</p>

  
</section>        </header>
        <section class="article-guts">
            <div itemprop="articleBody" class="article-content post-page">
                                    
<figure class="intro-image intro-left">
  <img src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/ASTON-MARTIN-RETURNS-TO-LE-MANS-TO-FIGHT-FOR-OVERALL-VICTORY-WITH-VALKYRIE-HYPERCAR_01-800x450.jpg" alt="A colorful render of a racing version of the Aston Martin Valkyrie hypercar">
      <figcaption class="caption"><div class="caption-text"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/ASTON-MARTIN-RETURNS-TO-LE-MANS-TO-FIGHT-FOR-OVERALL-VICTORY-WITH-VALKYRIE-HYPERCAR_01-scaled.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="1440" data-width="2560">Enlarge</a> <span class="sep">/</span> When Aston Martin first announced the Valkyrie it planned to take it to Le Mans. That plan got put on hold for a while, but now it's happening for real.</div><div class="caption-credit">Aston Martin</div></figcaption>  </figure>

  <aside id="social-left" class="social-left" aria-label="Read the comments or share this article">
          <a class="comment-count icon-comment-bubble-down" href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2023/10/aston-martin-will-take-a-detuned-valkyrie-hypercar-endurance-racing-in-2025/?comments=1">
      <h4 class="comment-count-before">reader comments</h4>
  
  <span class="comment-count-number">9</span>
  <span class="visually-hidden"> with </span>
  </a>
        </aside>




<!-- cache miss 62:single/related:432fad2fe3d4cc8669684e7bdcfadf12 --><!-- empty -->
<p>Aston Martin is set to return to the world's premier endurance race, the 24 Hours of Le Mans, with a prototype Valkyrie hypercar in 2025. The return to Le Mans also signals the marque joining the FIA World Endurance Championship (WEC) and the IMSA WeatherTech SportsCar Championship.</p>
<p>Often talked about in hushed tones by people in the know, the idea of Aston Martin's halo hypercar entering the top flight of endurance motorsport has long been wished for, and the firm's announcement is sure to make race fans happy. The Gaydon, UK, company intends to enter at least one Valkyrie in both WEC and IMSA from 2025, giving itself a chance to take the top step at Le Mans, the Rolex 24 at Daytona, and the 12 Hours of Sebring.</p>
<p>The basis for the competition car is set to be <a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2018/03/a-hybrid-bentley-and-million-dollar-track-cars-wow-at-the-geneva-motor-show/">the Aston Martin Valkyrie AMR Pro</a>, an even more hardcore version of the already rather raucous Valkyrie road car. The car with license plates boasts <a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2018/12/12-cylinders-11000rpm-aston-martins-new-engine-is-a-monster/">a Cosworth-developed 6.5-liter V12 packing</a> 1,000 hp (745 kW), mated to a 160 hp (120 kW) electric motor, giving it an F1-style kinetic energy recovery system. Its hybrid setup makes it a ferocious thing.</p>
<p>For those looking to keep their Valkyrie on the track only, the AMR Pro is the one to go for. The AMR Pro does without hybrid assistance but has smaller 18-inch wheels (the size required by race rules), Le Mans Prototype Michelin racing tires, F1-inspired carbon brakes, wilder aero, and no creature comforts inside. Aston Martin says the Valkyrie AMR Pro was always intended for Hypercar racing—even if that's PR spin, you can see how the company found it easy to use it as a basis for an endurance race car.</p>                                            <aside class="ad_wrapper" aria-label="In Content advertisement">
    <span class="ad_notice">Advertisement </span>    
    <div class="ad ad_instream"></div>    
</aside>
                                                        
<p>Aston Martin says it will "enhance" the Valkyrie's power unit to ensure it meets the punishing balance of performance requirements that the Hypercar class demands. This will mean its thunderous V12's peak power has to be taken down a peg or two, as the maximum permitted power output is 670 hp (500 kW). A less stressed engine should prove reliable, at least. [Shades of McLaren having to detune the F1's engine for the F1 GTR in 1995—Ed.]</p>
<figure class="image shortcode-img full-width" style="width:980px"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Aston_Martin_Valkyrie_AMR_Pro-scaled.jpg" class="enlarge" data-height="1707" data-width="2560" alt="In 2018, Aston Martin showed off the Valkyrie AMR Pro, which dropped the road legality and hybrid system for a set of slick tires. This will be the basis for the race car. "><img alt="In 2018, Aston Martin showed off the Valkyrie AMR Pro, which dropped the road legality and hybrid system for a set of slick tires. This will be the basis for the race car. " src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Aston_Martin_Valkyrie_AMR_Pro-980x653.jpg" width="980" height="653"></a><figcaption class="caption"><div class="caption-text"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Aston_Martin_Valkyrie_AMR_Pro-scaled.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="1707" data-width="2560">Enlarge</a> <span class="sep">/</span> In 2018, Aston Martin showed off the Valkyrie AMR Pro, which dropped the road legality and hybrid system for a set of slick tires. This will be the basis for the race car. </div><div class="caption-credit">Aston Martin</div></figcaption></figure>
<p>To manage the cars, Aston Martin is once again partnering with Heart of Racing, the team co-founded by Valve's Gabe Newell. Heart of Racing has been working with Aston Martin since its 2020 inception—mostly with GT3-spec Vantages in the IMSA GTD classes. The Valkyrie will be another string to an already successful bow, having already scored wins and an IMSA GTD class championship in 2022. Ian James, Heart of Racing’s team principal, is excited about the proposition of campaigning the Valkyrie. "Having the hypercar option with the Valkyrie, the ultimate hypercar, and to go to Le Mans and all the other races around the world… it was an opportunity we couldn’t miss," he said.</p>
<p>The Valkyrie won’t have hybrid or turbo assistance, which some of its competitors benefit from. James doesn’t think it will be a problem. "Hybrid systems are complex bits of kit and a source of struggle for competitors," he said. "The V12 is a proven architecture, and it’ll be de-stressed to the 700 hp range down from where it is. Reliability shouldn’t be an issue. The non-hybrid cars are smaller programs. I’m not sure what resources they have, but we’ll come better prepared."</p>
<p>Entering the top flight of endurance motorsport means that from 2025, Aston Martin will be the only manufacturer to compete in all levels of sports car and GT racing, as well as Formula One (Ferrari doesn't stoop so low as GT4 racing). From wealthy dentists upward, Aston has your motorsport back.</p>

                                                </div>

            
